[{'action': 'opened', 'author': 'zerovip', 'comment_id': None, 'datetime': '2021-01-03 06:58:31+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': '<!-- Please answer these questions before submitting your issue. Thanks! -->

### What version of Hugo are you using (`hugo version`)?

<pre>
$ hugo version
Hugo Static Site Generator v0.80.0/extended linux/amd64 BuildDate: unknown
</pre>

### Does this issue reproduce with the latest release?
Not tested.

### Issue
Hi, all.

After upgrading to version v0.80.0, there is an error:
```
start position out of bounds for x-byte string
```

I expected that `{{ substr "foo" 3 }}` gives me empty string, and this always works until v0.80.0.

I believe commit 64789fb5dcf8326f14f13d69a2576ae3aa2bbbaa caused this problem. It was
```golang
if start > len(asRunes) {
	return "", fmt.Errorf("start position out of bounds for %d-byte string", len(aStr))
```
before, and now:
```golang
if start > rlen-1 {
	return "", fmt.Errorf("start position out of bounds for %d-byte string", rlen)
}
```

Can removing "-1" fix this?

Thank you in advance, and happy new year!', 'title': "`substr` function gets error if `START` equals to string's length", 'type': 'issue'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'davidsneighbour', 'comment_id': 753583600.0, 'datetime': '2021-01-03 08:16:16+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': 'That error is expected because counting starts at 0, not 1. So the start position is actually out of bounds. That behaviour changed in 0.80.0 and is now the same way substr works in other languages. That it worked before was a bug ;). 

Is there a specific case where you would want an empty string to be returned? I would expect something like `{{ substr "foo" 0 0 }}` to do that trick. 

I am not sure if that is the updated version yet: https://gohugo.io/functions/substr/ - there was a PR for the documentation to fix up the explanations for the "new" substr handling some days ago.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'davidsneighbour', 'comment_id': 753583637.0, 'datetime': '2021-01-03 08:16:43+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_1', 'text': 'https://github.com/gohugoio/hugoDocs/commit/33021d451be5facf02b350169dd8a73fa74d72db', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'moorereason', 'comment_id': 753590944.0, 'datetime': '2021-01-03 09:34:24+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': "@username_0,
Sorry about the breaking change.  The previous substr implementation was pretty buggy.  We tried to ensure the new implementation matches PHP's substr.  After some looking around, various languages do this differently (empty string vs error).  I'm not dead set on keeping this error return, but I want a good argument for keeping the old behavior (other than it broke your site).

It's late here (power outage at work has me up at 3am), and I'm too tired to think clearly about this issue.  So, in the meantime...

Can you explain your use case?  How would you work around this issue?", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'zerovip', 'comment_id': 753595000.0, 'datetime': '2021-01-03 10:14:24+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': 'Thank you for your reply.

Sorry but I don't think it is related to where counting stars. The only difference is the valid bounds shrunk.

|  Environment   | code  | result |
|  ----  | ----  | :----:  |
| Hugo 0.79.1  | `{{ substr "foo" 0 }}` | "foo" |
|  | `{{ substr "foo" 1 }}` | "oo" |
|  | `{{ substr "foo" 2 }}` | "o" |
|  | `{{ substr "foo" 3 }}` | "" |
| Hugo 0.80.0  | `{{ substr "foo" 0 }}` | "foo" |
|  | `{{ substr "foo" 1 }}` | "oo" |
|  | `{{ substr "foo" 2 }}` | "o" |
|  | `{{ substr "foo" 3 }}` | error:  start position out of bounds for 3-byte string |
| Python  | `"foo"[0:]` | "foo" |
|  | `"foo"[1:]` | "oo" |
|  | `"foo"[2:]` | "o" |
|  | `"foo"[3:]` | "" |

--------

Sure I can explain my case:
I write
```
{{ $curr_page := . }}
{{ substr $curr_page.RelPermalink 4 }}
```
to get `example.html` from `/en/example.html`, then I combine it with
```
{{ range $.Site.Home.AllTranslations }}
    {{ .Permalink }}
```
to get, for example `/zh/example.html`. For the home page `/en/`, Hugo before 0.79.1 can successfully give me `/zh/`.

I am not familiar with Hugo, so I will be very happy and grateful if there is a better way to do so. Thank you in advance!

--------

In my opinion, there is no harm to get an empty string rather than get an error. Besides, I really don't have any good argument for that. So what do other people think?

--------

It is not in a hurry, so you can go to bed first. I am in China and it is six pm in the evening. We can listen to more others' opinions.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'jmooring', 'comment_id': 753647206.0, 'datetime': '2021-01-03 17:07:39+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_3', 'text': 'PHP doesn't complain either, and we refer to the PHP implementation in our documentation. Try this:
<https://www.tehplayground.com/mdhhZ1yQKelHccMS>

I encountered this breaking change a couple of days ago. I had some code that grabbed everything after the first character of a string, and I didn't provide a special case to check if the string was only a single character.

This worked in 0.79, though it is arguably lazy coding:

```
{{- $firstWord := "A" -}
{{- $firstCharacter := substr $firstWord 0 1 -}}
{{- $remainingCharacters := substr $firstWord 1 -}}
```

Changes required for 0.80:

```
{{- $firstWord := "A" -}
{{- $firstCharacter := substr $firstWord 0 1 -}}
{{- $remainingCharacters := "" -}}
{{- if gt (len $firstWord) 1 -}}
  {{- $remainingCharacters = substr $firstWord 1 -}}
{{- end -}}
```', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'zerovip', 'comment_id': 753648532.0, 'datetime': '2021-01-03 17:17:14+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': "Yes! You are right!!! Thank you very much. I tried PHP and Javascript, they all don't raise errors! Thank you very much! That must be a strong argument!", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'moorereason', 'comment_id': 753668530.0, 'datetime': '2021-01-03 19:59:28+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': "Interesting.  I assumed from the PHP docs that substr returning `false` in that scenario would raise an error somewhere, but apparently it doesn't.  `echo false` prints an empty string in PHP (`echo true` prints `1`).  ü§¶‍‚ôÇÔ∏è 

I think we can revert to the previous behavior by getting rid of the error and just returning an empty string.  I'll work on it.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'jmooring', 'comment_id': 753671298.0, 'datetime': '2021-01-03 20:25:42+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_3', 'text': '@username_2, Thank you.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'zerovip', 'comment_id': 753706855.0, 'datetime': '2021-01-04 00:57:09+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_0', 'text': "Thank you. Do we go further? I mean cancel the bound and always return empty string when `START` is greater than string's length. Because, PHP, javascript, and python all do like this.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
